  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_121087857" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/121087857" />
    <a title="Benjamin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30940-benjamin"><img alt="Benjamin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1174755731p2/30940.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/121087857?book_show_action=true">Sep 10, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Benjamin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Benjamin" href="/user/show/30940-benjamin">Benjamin</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30940-benjamin?shelf=audiobook">audiobook</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer121087857" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7209508972884975396">I want to be clear that I’m not making fun of people who do this, but almost every Goodreads review I’ve read of this book contains some description-by-simile: it&apos;s like Kafka; it&apos;s like Kafka and Auster collaborating; it&apos;s like Kafka&apos;s lovechild with Chesterton, writing his own bedtime story; it&apos;s like Kafka and Chesterton ejaculated into the skull of Lewis Carroll and made Lethem (early-mid Lethem) drink it; it&apos;s like Kafka possessed Neil Gaiman who then wrote the story with a typewriter of ca</span>
  <span id="freeText7209508972884975396" style="display:none">I want to be clear that I’m not making fun of people who do this, but almost every Goodreads review I’ve read of this book contains some description-by-simile: it's like Kafka; it's like Kafka and Auster collaborating; it's like Kafka's lovechild with Chesterton, writing his own bedtime story; it's like Kafka and Chesterton ejaculated into the skull of Lewis Carroll and made Lethem (early-mid Lethem) drink it; it's like Kafka possessed Neil Gaiman who then wrote the story with a typewriter of cats tuned to the key of a language spoken only by the blind men of Shambhala; it’s like Chandler, but, you know, less Chandleresque.<br /><br />There are many reasons why this book accretes comparisons to other writers and works*; but perhaps the most important is that it actually seems like a mixing of a number of genres and archetypes. Like any good Campbellian hero, the clerk Charles Unwin refuses the call to adventure--a promotion to detective status; but if you squint, he seems to have a Gogolian profile, as if he’s wandered out of “The Nose” or “The Overcoat”: the fastidious and, at first, unimaginative pencil pusher, in over his head. Unwin clerks for the Chandleresque Travis T. Sivart, who has the standard gold-heart of the noir detective, getting caught up with women and trying to do the right thing--“Down these mean streets,” etc., etc. Unwin’s case file titles--"The Three Deaths of Captain Baker”--smell Doylish to me (cf., “The Adventure of the Six Napoleons”), but maybe that’s just because Doyle gave us the cue for cute titles. The forgetful informant may be Borges’s Funes the memorious turned inside out. The metaphysical city has a Chestertonian dreaminess to it, keeping in mind the subtitle to <i>The Man Who Was Thursday</i>: “A Nightmare.” (I kept half-expecting for the steam-car driving Rook twins--described as incredibly hot and clay-faced--to turn out to be kiln-fired, steam-driven automatons and to come apart, much like the Marquis’s mask comes apart in Chesterton’s book.) Oh, and there’s shades of Kafka, here, as well. Calvino? Kobo Abe? Oh, and one more: the biloquist Enoch Hoffman seems like a take on the character of Carwin the Biloquist, the half-villainous character from Charles Brockden Brown’s <i>Wieland: or The Transformation</i> (1798), one of the earliest American novels.<br /><br />I’m sure you could continue this exercise and substitute your own literary history; but I’m not at all claiming here that Berry fails to be imaginative--I'm just saying that he’s playing a different game than we might expect. The seeming shades of others and allusions are not bugs (<i>das Ungeziefer</i>), but features: with so many stories going on beneath the hood, it’s not always clear where the story is going--and even more importantly, it’s not always clear how we’re supposed to feel about it. We want Unwin to win, since who doesn’t identify with hapless fools, am I right? But what counts as winning when it’s not even clear what the sides are here? I think the very multiplicity here also helps Berry avoid letting this story become a meta-consideration on any one particular genre; in other words, this isn’t <i>The Big Lebowski</i> or <i>Inherent Vice</i>, with their reconsiderations of California noir. Berry isn’t too concerned here, I think, with any one genre or author, but is more concerned with something like our reading experience.<br /><br />Now, that said, I also want to say that I think this is a very good book, and here's an anecdote as proof: I listened to this from the library, but due to some error, a couple pages were missing from my copy and I didn't want to go on without reading them; so, first, I turned to Google books and Amazon, but neither had all the missing pages; so I wrote my friend Chris an email, telling him that he might have to call me up and read me the missing pages; then I rode my bike to the not-so-local Borders and read the missing pages there. So, that's some indication of how I felt about this book: I didn't want to miss any of it. So it must be good.<br /><br />N.B. I’m almost sure I had drinks with Jed in college once (was he friends with Andy Small?), but I haven’t yet friended him on Facebook or Goodreads, so you know I think I can be honest here. <br /><br />*Not least of which: a) it’s fun to make crazy comparisons and satisfying, too. (I would argue that these comparisons satisfy our impulse for pattern recognizing); b) many famous hard-boiled detectives describe their world in an idiom of analogy and simile, cf., Chandler’s Philip Marlowe: “The light had an unreal greenish color, <b>like light filtered through an aquarium tank.</b> The plants filled the place, a forest of them, with nasty meaty leaves and stalks <b>like the newly washed fingers of dead men</b>” (<i>The Big Sleep</i>). In fact, in Berry’s book, the hard-boiled detective Sivart speaks in such similes often.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7209508972884975396" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


