    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_54590447" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/54590447" />
    <a title="Mike" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2201886-mike"><img alt="Mike" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1239392797p2/2201886.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/54590447?book_show_action=true">May 01, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mike" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mike" href="/user/show/2201886-mike">Mike</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Anyone</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer54590447" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16983328570592740308">“The Manual of Detection” is a quirky novel that combines mystery with “mystery”. Even after reading it, I’m not sure how it should be characterized. There is certainly detection and mystery. But there’s also a strange world with stranger rules and actors. It doesn’t try to be like anything else, yet it echoes classic detective novels and film.<br/><br/>We have a protagonist who spends most of the book confused over the disappearance of “his” Detective (he is his assigned clerk who receives and re-writes </span>
  <span id="freeText16983328570592740308" style="display:none">“The Manual of Detection” is a quirky novel that combines mystery with “mystery”. Even after reading it, I’m not sure how it should be characterized. There is certainly detection and mystery. But there’s also a strange world with stranger rules and actors. It doesn’t try to be like anything else, yet it echoes classic detective novels and film.<br /><br />We have a protagonist who spends most of the book confused over the disappearance of “his” Detective (he is his assigned clerk who receives and re-writes case details) and fighting his surprising elevation to the post of Detective. We have old solved, but now known-to-be-unsolved cases, femme fatales, enemies (real and imagined), and strange methods of communication and observation. The Agency for which he works is rigidly structured with hard boundaries between employee types and levels. (His hat is not appropriate to the 29th floor, but was suitable to the 14th.) Everyone has a place an in that place they are trained to remain.<br /><br />It’s not a weak novel: the author has clearly plotted it out so that the story remains tight and inventive in every chapter. Yet, the reader is pushed along with our man at the limit of his ability to comprehend. In a way, it reminded me of the Lemony Snicket novels (“A Series of Unfortunate Events” et al). The lead characters are always bumbling along lurching from one crisis to another. In the same way Charles Unwin (our man in the hat) does not control events, they control him – until the very end.<br /><br />As the book progresses so does our man. He will never be a conventional detective (nor does he want to be), but through his own perseverance and the kindness of many others he beats the odds and wins the day. (I’ll let the interested reader find out what that means on their own.)<br /><br />What set this novel apart from your average book about novices, good, and evil is the mystical elements that are woven into the story from the very beginning. It’s not simple premonition or prognostication that keeps things working. No, it is a form of institutionalized magic that underpins the Agency and its adversaries. I don’t know what suggested these ideas to the author, but they make this book unique.<br /><br />It’s possible that many readers won’t appreciate this inventiveness. It certainly makes the book harder to grasp, but if you do I think you will be impressed by the creativity and the execution of the plot. I waited along time to actually read this book, but it was worth every second. I hope you like it, also.<br /><br />FYI - .It’s not a Children’s or YA book, despite my reference to Lemony Snicket.<br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16983328570592740308" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


