  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_59027351" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/59027351" />
    <a title="Peter" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1830226-peter"><img alt="Peter" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/59027351?book_show_action=true">Jun 09, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Peter" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Peter" href="/user/show/1830226-peter">Peter</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer59027351" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17700389303383560081">I had a bit of trouble getting into the Manual of Detection. I felt like I was in a Magritte painting where things are strange and precise, and but cold and lifeless. The main character barely shows any humanity until 3 or 4 chapters in when he waves to some school children. The murder of a colleague discovered earlier creates only a bout of self-absorption. <br/><br/>Around page 96, however, the book picked up for me so that I had trouble putting it down. The protagonist develops and his character flaws </span>
  <span id="freeText17700389303383560081" style="display:none">I had a bit of trouble getting into the Manual of Detection. I felt like I was in a Magritte painting where things are strange and precise, and but cold and lifeless. The main character barely shows any humanity until 3 or 4 chapters in when he waves to some school children. The murder of a colleague discovered earlier creates only a bout of self-absorption. <br /><br />Around page 96, however, the book picked up for me so that I had trouble putting it down. The protagonist develops and his character flaws are addressed. The story moved along, revealing one surprise after another, in a tightly constructed hard-boiled mystery right at home in the genre. <br /><br />What makes the book great were all the layers on top of the story. The book plays between its own structure, a manual set in the story, and the main character's own writings. There is a huge Surrealist element to the book, which at first seems like so much nonsense, but is resolved at the end. The book is complex and detailed enough that it merits a second read, just to see if it holds together on closer inspection. In my system, 5 stars go to books that transcend their genre.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17700389303383560081" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


