    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_193668597" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/193668597" />
    <a title="Candace Burton" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5943483-candace-burton"><img alt="Candace Burton" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1312302786p2/5943483.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/193668597?book_show_action=true">Aug 02, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Candace Burton" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Candace Burton" href="/user/show/5943483-candace-burton">Candace Burton</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer193668597" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14600398947317468488">film noir. gothic fantasy. the thursday next series, the thin man movies, spenser and hawk. if you like any of these, you will likely enjoy this book as much as i did. it is splendidly and almost seamlessly written. the prose is intense and carries a depth that i don&apos;t find often in any but the most tragic of fictions--and this is no tragedy. it&apos;s not a comedy, it&apos;s definitely not a romance, but really just a good story with some decidedly whacked out elements. charles unwin, hapless clerk to th</span>
  <span id="freeText14600398947317468488" style="display:none">film noir. gothic fantasy. the thursday next series, the thin man movies, spenser and hawk. if you like any of these, you will likely enjoy this book as much as i did. it is splendidly and almost seamlessly written. the prose is intense and carries a depth that i don't find often in any but the most tragic of fictions--and this is no tragedy. it's not a comedy, it's definitely not a romance, but really just a good story with some decidedly whacked out elements. charles unwin, hapless clerk to the great detective travis sivart, finds himself suddenly and unwelcomely thrust from his comfortable desk on the 14th floor of "the agency" headlong into the investigation of sivart's disappearance. the supporting cast includes his ertwhile assistant emily (apparently narcoleptic), various detectival suits, and the entire spectrum of Caligari's Travels-No-More carnival--inexplicably rotting away at the edge of the scene. like the carnival and unwin's life, the whole thing threatens to spin completely out of control more than once, but berry hauls it all back to earth and somehow manages to tie things up tidily by the end. a wild rumpus and a good one for the thinking reader.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14600398947317468488" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


