<div id="review_1769811537" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1769811537" />
    <a title="DeAnna Knippling" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3166570-deanna-knippling"><img alt="DeAnna Knippling" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442526565p2/3166570.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1769811537?book_show_action=true">Sep 27, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="DeAnna Knippling" class="user" itemprop="url" name="DeAnna Knippling" href="/user/show/3166570-deanna-knippling">DeAnna Knippling</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1769811537" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8017937981763619118">Most of this book is five-star. However, the author did not stick the landing - and I&apos;m picky about landings.<br/><br/>A run fead, a nonsense work that starts messing with your brain. First paragraph:<br/><br/>&quot;Lest details be mistaken for clues, note that Mr. Charles Unwin, lifetime resident of this city, rode his bicycle to work every day, even when it was raining. He had contrived a method to keep his umbrella open while pedaling, by hooking the umbrella&apos;s handle around the bicycle&apos;s handlebar. This method made </span>
  <span id="freeText8017937981763619118" style="display:none">Most of this book is five-star. However, the author did not stick the landing - and I'm picky about landings.<br /><br />A run fead, a nonsense work that starts messing with your brain. First paragraph:<br /><br />"Lest details be mistaken for clues, note that Mr. Charles Unwin, lifetime resident of this city, rode his bicycle to work every day, even when it was raining. He had contrived a method to keep his umbrella open while pedaling, by hooking the umbrella's handle around the bicycle's handlebar. This method made the bicycle less maneuverable and reduced the scope of Unwin's vision, but if his daily schedule was to accommodate an unofficial trip to Central Terminal for unofficial reasons, then certain risks were to be expected."<br /><br />A lighthearted Terry Gilliam, if you can imagine that. <br /><br />Anyhow, it's the first novel of a short-story writer, very ambitious, but tends toward excessive chaos and "weren't you paying attention to the hidden clue on page xyz" obscurity toward the end. I look forward to reading future novels from the author as he gets his chops.<br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="8017937981763619118" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


